  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Ellicott's Commentary for English Readers",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(5) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Moreover four thousand were porters.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "—Literally, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "and four thousand",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (are to be) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "warders.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (Comp. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1Chronicles 9:21-27",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".) Reuss thinks 4,000 warders too many; but the different clans went on duty in turn.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "And four thousand praised the Lord . . .—Rather, and four thousand (are to be) praising the Lord with the instruments that I have made for praising. (On “praising,” see 1Chronicles 16:4.) We have here an interesting reference to the fact that David was not only a minstrel and inspired psalmist, but also an inventor of stringed instruments. So the prophet Amos (1Chronicles 6:5) speaks of the effeminate nobles of Israel, “who prattle on the mouth of the nebel, that invent themselves instruments of music, like David.” The reference is repeated in Nehemiah 12:36.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "And four thousand praised the Lord",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " . . .—Rather, ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "and four thousand",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " (are to be) ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "praising the Lord with the instruments that I have made for praising.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " (On “praising,” see ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "1Chronicles 16:4",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ".) We have here an interesting reference to the fact that David was not only a minstrel and inspired psalmist, but also an inventor of stringed instruments. So the prophet Amos (",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "1Chronicles 6:5",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ") speaks of the effeminate nobles of Israel, “who prattle on the mouth of the ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "nebel,",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " that invent themselves instruments of music, like David.” The reference is repeated in ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Nehemiah 12:36",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ".",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Which I have made.—This expression proves that 1Chronicles 23:4-5 should be within inverted commas, as representing a spoken decree of David. Ewald thinks that the narrative is interrupted in 1Chronicles 23:5 by a fragmentary quotation from an ancient poet who speaks in the name of Jehovah, characterising the musicians as “those whom I have formed to sing my praise.” (But see 2Chronicles 7:6.)",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "Which I have made.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "—This expression proves that ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "1Chronicles 23:4-5",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " should be within inverted commas, as representing a spoken decree of David. Ewald thinks that the narrative is interrupted in ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "1Chronicles 23:5",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " by a fragmentary quotation from an ancient poet who speaks in the name of Jehovah, characterising ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "the musicians",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " as “those whom I have formed to sing my praise.” (But see ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "2Chronicles 7:6",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ".)",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
